SECTION 1: DIAGNOSTIC REPORT :  Current AI Failures at AfyaTech
AfyaTech is a Nairobi-based digital health startup connecting Kenyans in informal settlements and rural counties to primary healthcare via USSD, SMS, and a lightweight Android app. After an internal audit, four critical AI failures were identified across the four domains.
Domain 1 - Prompting Failure  Framework: AIM + MAP
Framework: AIM (Actor–Input–Mission)
Critical Gap: Symptom triage prompts are written in vague Human English with no defined Actor, no scoped Input, and no measurable Mission.
Real Example: AfyaTech's current prompt reads: 'Help the patient understand their symptoms.' The AI responds with a generic WHO copy that ignores Nairobi's actual disease burden malaria, typhoid, and TB.
Real-World Harm: A mother in Kibera describes her child's fever and cough. The AI returns a broad flu advisory, missing a probable malaria+TB co-infection pattern common in that microclimate. She delays seeking care for 72 hours. The child is hospitalised.


Domain 2  AI Fluency Failure - Framework: 4D Framework
Framework: 4D (Delegation, Description, Discernment, Diligence)
Critical Gap: The Delegation dimension is absent. No temperature calibration, no RAG source connected, and no negative prompting. The AI 'auto-pilots' clinical conversations without a defined persona or performance guardrails.
Real Example: When a user from Mombasa asks about chest pain in Swahili, the AI switches to English mid-conversation and suggests 'schedule an appointment with your cardiologist'  ignoring that Mombasa Coast General Hospital's cardiology unit has a 6-week public queue.
Real-World Harm: Patients in coastal counties receive medically accurate but contextually useless guidance. Trust collapses. USSD drop-off rates spike 38% after the first AI exchange.


Domain 3  Ethics Failure  Framework: TRACK + OASIS
Framework: TRACK (Training Data, Representation, Amplification, Counterfactuals, Kill Switch) + OASIS (Opt-in, Anonymisation, Sovereignty, Intentional Retention, Security)
Critical Gap: AfyaTech's symptom-classification model was trained on NHIF (National Hospital Insurance Fund) data from Nairobi's formal private hospitals. Community health data from OASIS-compliant community units in Turkana or Marsabit does not exist in the training set.
Real Example: Pastoral women in Turkana describing symptoms consistent with cervical cancer receive a triage score of 'low urgency' because the AI lacks representation of their presentation patterns. Their occupational category  'livestock keeper'  is not in the training corpus.
Real-World Harm: Late-stage cancer diagnoses increase among marginalised communities. The AI amplifies the existing healthcare inequality rather than correcting it  the definition of algorithmic violence.


Domain 4  Agent Orchestration Failure  Framework: RANK + TRAIL
Framework: RANK (Role, Authority, Notification, Kill Switch) + TRAIL (Transient, Relational, Archival, Inheritance, Land Rights)
Critical Gap: AfyaTech deployed a Referral Agent that books NHIF-covered clinics autonomously. No authority limits were defined. No kill switch exists. Memory inheritance between the Triage Agent and Referral Agent passes raw patient PII including HIV status markers.
Real Example: The Referral Agent booked a patient for an HIV follow-up at a clinic in their home village without confirming confidentiality preference. The booking SMS was sent to a shared family phone number.
Real-World Harm: Stigma exposure. The patient's HIV status became known to family members. This is a direct violation of Kenya's HIV and AIDS Prevention and Control Act (2006) and the Data Protection Act (2019).



SECTION 2: REDESIGNED AI SYSTEM  Fixing Each Gap
2.1 Prompting Fix: AIM + MAP Applied to Symptom Triage
The following prompt replaces AfyaTech's vague triage instruction. Labels show each framework component.

REDESIGNED PROMPT  AIM LAYER
[A - Actor] You are AfyaTech's Community Health Navigator, a trained clinical triage assistant fluent in Swahili and Sheng, operating within Kenya's Community Health Strategy (2020–2030). You are NOT a doctor. You do not diagnose. You assess urgency and recommend care pathways.
[I - Input] The patient has submitted the following symptoms via USSD/SMS: {symptom_string}. Their county is {county}, age group is {age_bracket}, and NHIF status is {nhif_active}. Cross-reference against Kenya's top 10 disease burden by county (malaria, TB, typhoid, pneumonia, diarrhoeal disease).
[M - Mission] Produce a triage response in under 160 characters (one SMS). Output format: URGENCY LEVEL (Red/Yellow/Green)  LIKELY CONDITION (2 words max) | NEXT STEP (specific facility or home care). Do not mention conditions you cannot confirm. Do not use English if the patient wrote in Swahili.
MAP LAYER
[M – Memory] Retain the last 3 exchanges in session memory to detect symptom escalation patterns across a conversation.
[A - Assets] Attach Kenya MOH Community Health Strategy 2020–2030 guidelines, county-level disease burden data (KNBS 2023), and AfyaTech's verified clinic database (updated weekly from NHIF portal).
[P - Prompt/Actions] If URGENCY = Red, trigger action: auto-send patient's GPS-nearest emergency facility via M-Pesa Lipa Na bill pay shortcut. Log case to AfyaTech dashboard for CHW (Community Health Worker) follow-up within 2 hours.


2.2 Fluency Fix: 4D Framework Applied to Patient Consultations
AfyaTech's consultation flow is redesigned using the full 4D Framework, bringing clinical context, language fidelity, and responsible deployment together.

4D Dimension
AfyaTech Implementation
Delegation
Goal: triage urgency and route to care. Platform: Claude Haiku (low-cost, fast inference for USSD latency constraints). Budget cap: $0.002 per session. Regulatory constraint: Kenya DPA 2019  no raw PII in API calls.
Description
Product: single SMS response (≤160 chars) in patient's language. Process: Chain-of-Thought ('reason step-by-step against Kenya disease burden before outputting'). Persona: 'supportive CHW elder sister, not a clinical authority'. Delimiter: ### separates system instruction from patient input. Negative prompt: 'Do NOT suggest private hospital referrals unless NHIF tier permits. Do NOT use medical jargon. Do NOT mention HIV unless the patient raises it.'
Discernment
Product: CHW supervisor reviews 10 random triage outputs daily. Process: AI must show a reasoning chain when urgency = Red. Performance: weekly session-dropout audit  if dropout >25% at any exchange point, trigger UX review.
Diligence
Bias check: audit quarterly for county-level disparate urgency ratings. Transparency: every AI response includes a footer 'This is AfyaTech AI, not a doctor.' Deployment: all triage outputs feed a human CHW dashboard before any Red-alert action fires.


Technical Controls
Temperature Setting: 0.2 - Low, for clinical accuracy. We are not generating creative content; we are triaging human health. High temperature (creative exploration) is dangerous here.
RAG Source: Kenya MOH Disease Surveillance Reports (real-time integration via MOH Open Data Portal API) + AfyaTech county-level clinic availability database. Eliminates hallucinated clinics and names  a known failure mode.
Negative Prompt: Do NOT mention conditions not consistent with Kenya's endemic disease profile. Do NOT recommend diagnostic tests unavailable at Level 2/3 facilities. Do NOT switch languages mid-conversation.


2.3 Ethics Fix: TRACK + OASIS Applied to Training Data Governance
The data governance decision: whether to expand AfyaTech's triage model training data to include CHW case records from ASAL (Arid and Semi-Arid Land) counties  Turkana, Marsabit, Garissa. This is the right decision, but it must be done with precision.

TRACK Analysis
T - Training Data: Current corpus: 92% NHIF private clinic records from Nairobi/Mombasa. Zero data from ASAL counties. The model has never 'seen' a pastoralist presentation pattern.
R - Representation: Occupational categories like 'livestock keeper', 'charcoal seller', 'boda boda rider' are absent. The AI defaults to 'unemployed' — triggering lower-urgency scores.
A - Amplification: Marginalised communities receive systematically lower triage urgency scores, amplifying the existing health access gap. This is not neutral — it is algorithmic discrimination.
C - Counterfactuals: Test: submit identical symptom string with occupation = 'office worker, Nairobi' vs 'livestock keeper, Turkana'. If urgency scores differ with no clinical basis, bias is confirmed. Run this test monthly.
K - Kill Switch: If counterfactual test shows >15% urgency score disparity by county or occupation: pause the model, escalate to AfyaTech Clinical Ethics Board within 24 hours. USSD reverts to static MOH symptom guide.


OASIS Protocol for ASAL Data Expansion
O - Opt-in by Design: AfyaTech will partner with Turkana County Community Health Units. CHWs will explain data use in Turkana language before any records are shared. Consent forms in English + Turkana (no digital literacy assumed).
A - Anonymisation Depth: Apply k-anonymity (k≥10): no individual patient record can be re-identified from symptom-county-age-occupation combination. Strip village-level identifiers. Reviewed by AfyaTech's Data Protection Officer.
S - Sovereignty First: Regulation cited: Kenya Data Protection Act, 2019 (Section 25 — data localisation). All ASAL community health records stored on AWS Africa (Cape Town) region servers. No transfer to US/EU servers without explicit written consent from the county government.
I - Intentional Retention: Raw CHW case records auto-deleted after 90 days. Only anonymised, aggregated symptom patterns retained in the training corpus. Cron job scheduled; deletion confirmed monthly by DPO.
S - Security as Ritual: End-to-end encryption using AES-256. USSD sessions use ephemeral session tokens. Regular penetration testing by CyberSmart Africa (Nairobi-based security firm). Encryption is not a checkbox, it is reviewed at every sprint.


2.4 Agent Orchestration Fix: RANK + TRAIL Applied to Triage-to-Referral Handoff
AfyaTech's redesigned agent system has two agents: Triage Agent (TA) and Referral Agent (RA). Their handoff is governed by RANK authority limits and TRAIL memory rules.

RANK Framework  Agent 1: Triage Agent (TA)
Role (singular): Assess symptom urgency only. Output: Urgency level (Red/Yellow/Green) + likely condition category. Nothing else.
Authority Limits: TA may NOT: book appointments, access NHIF records, send external communications, or store any patient data beyond the current session. TA may only: read the session's symptom input + query the MOH RAG source.
Notification Triggers: Alert human CHW supervisor when: (1) Urgency = Red; (2) Patient mentions suicide/self-harm; (3) Symptom string matches notifiable disease pattern (cholera, meningitis); (4) Session drops mid-triage with Red symptoms present.
Kill Switch Protocol: USSD command *#AFYA# (274927#) instantly halts TA and routes patient to static MOH helpline 0800 723 253 (toll-free). Command accessible to any AfyaTech operations staff member, 24/7.


RANK Framework  Agent 2: Referral Agent (RA)
Role (singular): Match urgency level to nearest NHIF-covered facility and communicate booking option to patient. Nothing else.
Authority Limits: RA may NOT: book without patient confirmation (two-step consent via USSD reply '1 = YES'). RA may NOT send SMS to any number other than the verified session number. RA may NOT access HIV status, mental health flags, or prior consultation history.
Notification Triggers: Alert human when: (1) No NHIF-covered facility within 10km; (2) Patient rejects 3 consecutive referrals (may indicate access barrier needing CHW intervention); (3) Facility capacity = 0 (overflow state).
Kill Switch Protocol: Same *#AFYA# command halts RA. Additionally, any AfyaTech clinic partner can SMS 'PAUSE-RA' to the system number to freeze all bookings to that facility.


TRAIL Memory Architecture  TA→RA Handoff
Transient Memory: TA holds: session symptom string, urgency score, county, NHIF status. Deleted at session end.
Relational Memory: Opt-in only. If patient consents (USSD: '2 = Save my health profile'), county and preferred language stored for future sessions. No symptoms stored.
Archival Memory: Anonymised urgency-by-county aggregates retained for model retraining. Never raw PII. Reviewed by the Ethics Board before the retraining cycle.
Inheritance Rules: TA → RA handoff packet contains ONLY: {urgency_level}, {county}, {nhif_active}, {preferred_language}, {session_id}. Raw symptom string is NOT passed. HIV-related flags are NOT passed. The RA is clinically blind to the diagnosis.
Land Rights: All memory stored under Kenya Data Protection Act 2019 on AWS Africa (Cape Town). AfyaTech's DPO holds sole authority over data export requests. No Silicon Valley server touch.



