SECTION 4: REFLECTION  : How This Course Changed My Understanding
From Efficiency to Dignity: A Chief AI Officer's Reckoning
Before this course, I thought of AI as an efficiency engine and a faster calculator. AfyaTech's early deployments reflected this thinking: automate the triage, automate the referral, watch the numbers improve. The AI Safari dismantled that assumption methodically, terrain by terrain.
The moment my thinking shifted was in the Ethical Savannah, when the TRACK framework asked me to run a counterfactual. I submitted AfyaTech's triage model with two identical symptom strings, one attributed to a Nairobi office worker, one to a Turkana livestock keeper. The urgency scores differed by two levels. Same fever. Same cough. Same duration. Different person, different outcome. That is not a technical glitch. That is a values choice embedded in training data, invisible until you go looking for it. The discomfort of that discovery was, as the professor said, 'wisdom growing where recklessness once lived.'
The OASIS protocol and the concept of data sovereignty reframed everything. I had been thinking about patient data as a resource to optimise  more data, better model, better outcomes. Now I understand that data generated by a Marsabit community health worker belongs to that community. AfyaTech is a steward, not an owner. This is not a philosophical nicety; it is the difference between a healthcare tool and a new form of colonial extraction.
The Agent Savannah's RANK framework gave me the practical language I had been missing. I now know that deploying an agent without a kill switch is not innovation, it is negligence. AfyaTech's Referral Agent had no authority limits, no notification triggers, and no kill switch. It was a rogue system we called progress. Defining Role, Authority, Notification, and Kill Switch before writing a single line of code is now my non-negotiable first step.
The baobab does not grow fast. It grows deep. This course taught me to build AI the way the Savannah builds ecosystems  with patience, accountability, and an understanding that every root you lay reaches further than you can see. Safari njema.




